The country on Tuesday recorded 24 Covid-19 deaths, the highest in a day, raising the death toll to 1,154. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe, in a statement, announced that 1,344 more people had tested positive, raising the caseload to 64,588. The new cases were from a sample size of 7,162, representing a positivity rate of 18.7 per cent. Most of the new cases were Kenyans, except 45. “A total of 1,266 patients are admitted to various health facilities countrywide, while 5,898 are in home-based isolation and care. Fifty-eight patients are in the ICU,” the CS said. He announced that 436 people had recovered, 297 from home-based care, while 139 were discharged from hospitals. The total recoveries now stand at 43,095. In terms of distribution per county, Nairobi recorded the highest number with 322 new cases, followed by Kiambu with 221. Mombasa was third with 133, Laikipia had 72, Uasin Gishu 66, Kericho 65, Nakuru 63, Kajiado 43 and Kilifi 40. Kisumu recorded 36 cases, Kwale and Migori 32 each, Machakos 30, Baringo 20, Bomet 19, Nandi 16, Meru 13, Nyeri 12, while Kisii, Embu and Mandera each had 11 cases.  Kakamega, Murang’a and Nyamira each had eight cases, while Turkana and Elgeyo Marakwet recorded five. Other counties with new cases include Nyandarua, Narok, Kirinyaga and Trans Nzoia, each with four cases; Tharaka Nithi, Vihiga and West Pokot, each with three cases; Bungoma, Taita Taveta, Wajir, Busia, Makueni, Samburu, Homa Bay and Siaya with two cases each; and Kitui with one.